  number = {1},
  pages = {9--26},
  issn = {0046-2772},
  abstract = {A res project was conducted to extend soc exchange theory to a situation of exchanging unlike behaviors. F judges (N=90) rated the performance of M's (accomplices of the exp'er) in a creativity task. A 2*2*2 factorial design manipulated the variables of cost to the judge for inaccurate ratings, attractiveness of the M performer \& dependency of the performer's outcomes on the judge's ratings. The basic expectations were generated from soc exchange theory \& signif'ly supported. Under low cost, \& to a lesser extent also under high cost, creativity ratings would be given more to highly attractive than to less attractive performers. This result pattern was not affected by the dependency manipulation as could tentatively be expected on the basis of the altruism \& ingratiation phenomena. These findings are discussed in relation to those of a previous study using M judges \& F performers \& diff's are interpreted in terms of the appropriateness of the behavior according to sex role prescriptions. The discussion suggests the need for res directed toward determining the conditions which predispose people to choose one soc exchange rule over another. Modified HA.},
